[White "White Repertoire"]
[Black "Jobava London"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 {1.d4 opens the center and grabs space. It is the foundation of the Jobava London, where White quickly adds Nc3 and Bf4 for natural development and pressure, without heavy theory.}
1... d5 {Takes the classical center and establishes a presence on d5/e4. White continues the Jobava plan: Nc3, Bf4 and pressure.}
( 1... e5 {An attempt to break in the center. Usually after dxe5 lines and files open in favor of White's developed pieces.} 2. dxe5 {Opens the center and exploits ...e5. After the exchanges the f4-bishop and b5-knight are very active, and Black often runs into tactical trouble around c7 and d5.}
2... Nc6 {Active development, but it weakens the defense of c7 and invites Nb5 with threats of Nxc7+ and Nd6 — exactly the structure White welcomes.}
( 2... Bc5 {In the 1...e5 gambit line, develops with tempo against f2. White develops with Nf3 and Nc3 and keeps the extra pawn.} 3. Nf3 {Natural development supporting d4 and e5, preparing short castling and completing White's solid setup.}
3... d6 {A restrained move preparing ...e5 or a hypermodern setup. White grabs the center with e4 and plays on space.}
4. exd6 {The pawn recaptures and keeps the extra material from the gambit, while opening lines that favor White's development.}
4... Ne7 {A knight heading to g6 to pressure e5. White completes development and keeps the material edge.}
5. Nc3 {The signature move of the Jobava London: the knight develops to c3, pressuring d5 and e4 without blocking the c-pawn. This keeps the Nb5 jump and fast pressure available, unlike the classical London with c3.} )
( 2... d6 {A restrained move preparing ...e5 or a hypermodern setup. White grabs the center with e4 and plays on space.} 3. Nf3 {Natural development supporting d4 and e5, preparing short castling and completing White's solid setup.} )
3. Nf3 {Natural development supporting d4 and e5, preparing short castling and completing White's solid setup.}
3... Qe7 {In the 1...e5 line, tries to regain the pawn by pressuring e5. White develops carefully (Nf3, Nc3) and keeps the extra material.}
4. Nc3 {The signature move of the Jobava London: the knight develops to c3, pressuring d5 and e4 without blocking the c-pawn. This keeps the Nb5 jump and fast pressure available, unlike the classical London with c3.} )
( 1... e6 {Supports d5 and opens the f8-bishop, but temporarily blocks the c8-bishop (the "bad bishop"). White continues e3 and natural development.} 2. Nc3 {The signature move of the Jobava London: the knight develops to c3, pressuring d5 and e4 without blocking the c-pawn. This keeps the Nb5 jump and fast pressure available, unlike the classical London with c3.}
2... d5 {Takes the classical center and establishes a presence on d5/e4. White continues the Jobava plan: Nc3, Bf4 and pressure.}
( 2... Nf6 {Develops the knight and controls e4 and d5. White will usually reply Bf4 with calm development.} 3. e4 {Grabs the full center. Against a hypermodern setup (...g6/...d6) White builds a big center and prepares e5 to seize the initiative.} )
( 2... Nc6 {Active development, but it weakens the defense of c7 and invites Nb5 with threats of Nxc7+ and Nd6 — exactly the structure White welcomes.} 3. e4 {Grabs the full center. Against a hypermodern setup (...g6/...d6) White builds a big center and prepares e5 to seize the initiative.} )
3. Bf4 {The dark-squared bishop comes outside the pawn chain before e3 — the heart of the system. From f4 it pressures c7 and Black's kingside and prepares ideas like Nb5.}
3... Nf6 {Develops the knight and controls e4 and d5. White will usually reply Bf4 with calm development.}
( 3... Nc6 {Active development, but it weakens the defense of c7 and invites Nb5 with threats of Nxc7+ and Nd6 — exactly the structure White welcomes.} 4. Nb5 {The knight jumps to b5, exploiting the weakness of c7. Threats of Nxc7+ (forking king and rook) and an invasion on d6 arise — a practical, aggressive move typical of the Jobava.}
4... Bd6 {Offers to trade White's important f4-bishop. White will consider Bxd6 (giving Black a doubled structure) or retreating to keep the bishop, depending on the position.}
5. Nxd6+ {Trades off the d6-bishop — Black's good bishop — forcing ...cxd6, which leaves Black with doubled, heavy pawns on the d-file.}
5... cxd6 {Recaptures on d6, but is left with doubled, heavy pawns on the d-file — exactly the structural edge White was after.}
6. Nf3 {Natural development supporting d4 and e5, preparing short castling and completing White's solid setup.} )
( 3... Bd6 {Offers to trade White's important f4-bishop. White will consider Bxd6 (giving Black a doubled structure) or retreating to keep the bishop, depending on the position.} 4. e3 {A foundational move: it opens the f1-bishop, reinforces d4 and completes a solid setup. White now has a sturdy London structure with the bishop already active outside the chain.}
4... Nf6 {Develops the knight and controls e4 and d5. White will usually reply Bf4 with calm development.}
5. Nf3 {Natural development supporting d4 and e5, preparing short castling and completing White's solid setup.} )
( 3... Bb4 {Pins the c3-knight and pressures the center. White answers a3 (to question the bishop) or Ne2 (to support c3 and keep the g4 break flexible).} 4. e3 {A foundational move: it opens the f1-bishop, reinforces d4 and completes a solid setup. White now has a sturdy London structure with the bishop already active outside the chain.}
4... Nf6 {Develops the knight and controls e4 and d5. White will usually reply Bf4 with calm development.}
5. Ne2 {To e2 rather than f3: this keeps the f-pawn free for a future g4 push, supports the c3-knight, and if Black trades with ...Bxc3 White recaptures with the knight and keeps a good structure. A flexible move typical against ...Bb4.}
5... Ne4 {An active central knight that invites trades and tries to ease Black's game. White usually responds with a3/f3 or development that exploits the central stability. An inaccuracy that plays into White's hands.}
6. a3 {Questions the bishop on b4: if ...Bxc3 White opens a file, improves the structure and keeps the bishop pair; if the bishop retreats White has gained a tempo and space.} )
